nodes.id: Macro BIM Adoption- Comparative Market Analysis.pdf
nodes.label: Macro BIM Adoption: Comparative Market Analysis
nodes.desc: This paper presents a comparative market analysis of macro BIM adoption across 21 countries, using five conceptual models. It validates these models with expert input and discusses their application in assessing BIM adoption policies and creating policy roadmaps.

nodes.id: The Five Components of BIM Performance Measurement.pdf
nodes.label: The Five Components of BIM Performance Measurement
nodes.desc: This paper identifies five complementary components developed to enable BIM performance assessment: [1] BIM Capability Stages, [2] BIM Maturity Levels, [3] BIM Competencies, [4] Organisational Scales and [5] Granularity Levels. It explores these components as a systematic method to understand, assess and improve BIM performance.

nodes.id: Lifecycle information transformation and exchange for delivering and managing digital and physical assets.pdf
nodes.label: Lifecycle information transformation and exchange...
nodes.desc: This paper introduces the Lifecycle Information Transformation and Exchange (LITE) framework, a conceptual structure that lays the groundwork for a new approach to asset and project lifecycle information exchange and management. The framework accounts for the proliferation of technological innovations enabling the integration of asset lifecycle information into Design, Construction, and Operation activities.

nodes.label: Macro-BIM Adoption, Conceptual Structures
nodes.desc: This paper introduces a number of macro-adoption models, matrices and charts for systematically assessing BIM adoption across markets and informing the structured development of country-speciﬁc BIM adoption policies.

nodes.id: A competency knowledge-base for BIM learning.pdf
nodes.label: A Competency Knowledge-Base for BIM Learning
nodes.desc: This paper introduces a conceptual workflow to identify, classify, and aggregate BIM competency items. It acts as a knowledge-base for BIM learners and learning providers, which can be used to develop BIM learning modules to satisfy the learning requirements of varied audiences.

nodes.id: An integrated approach to BIM competency assessment, acquisition and application.pdf
nodes.label: An integrated approach to BIM competency assessment, acquisition and application
nodes.desc: This paper focuses on individual BIM competencies, the building blocks of organisational capability. It introduces taxonomies and conceptual models to clarify how individual competencies may be filtered, classified, and aggregated into a seed competency inventory. It also discusses the benefits of a competency-based approach to industry and academia, and explores future conceptual and tool development efforts to enable industry-wide BIM performance assessment and improvement.

nodes.label: Building Information Modelling Maturity Matrix
nodes.desc: This document introduces the BIM Maturity Matrix (BIm³), a performance measurement and improvement tool which identifies the correlation between BIM Stages, Competency Sets, Maturity Levels and Organisational Scales.

nodes.label: Model Uses: Foundations for a Modular Requirements Clarification Language
nodes.desc: This paper introduces the Model Uses concept, comprising a Model Uses Taxonomy and a Model Uses List. Model Uses are the intended, planned, or expected project deliverables resulting from generating, collaborating, or linking models to external databases. It explores the conceptual foundations of Model Uses and then provides practical examples of how this modular language assists in identifying BIM project requirements and facilitating project delivery.

nodes.id: Building Information Modelling- conceptual constructs and performance improvement tools.pdf
nodes.label: BIM: Conceptual Constructs and Performance Improvement Tools
nodes.desc: This doctoral thesis by Bilal Succar explores the knowledge structures underlying the BIM domain and introduces tools for BIM learning, assessment, and performance improvement. It delivers a BIM framework composed of three axes representing the main knowledge structures, extended through concepts and tools for performance assessment of individuals, organizations, and teams. It presents a knowledge structure for building BIM performance improvement initiatives.

nodes.label: Building Information Modelling: Point of Adoption
nodes.desc: This paper introduces the Point of Adoption (PoA) model which integrates concepts of BIM readiness, implementation, and diffusion into a single visual model. The PoA model facilitates the assessment of current organisational abilities, and clarifies a step-wise approach to BIM adoption and continuous performance improvement.

nodes.label: BIM Education, BIM in Practice
nodes.desc: A collection of three documents from the BIM Education Working Group (EWG) focusing on BIM education, BIM learners, BIM learning providers, and the BIM learning spectrum. It identifies key educational principles for collaborative BIM education in Australia. Documents include E1: BIM Education & BIM Learners, E2: BIM Learning Providers, and E3: BIM Learning Spectrum.

nodes.id: Towards a taxonomy of built asset lifecycle information coupling.pdf
nodes.label: Towards a taxonomy of built asset lifecycle information coupling
nodes.desc: This paper proposes a taxonomy of Built Asset Lifecycle Information Couples which provides the core elements, definitions and characteristics framing the physical-digital coupling of assets and resources in the built asset industry. The proposed taxonomy developed in this paper contributes to the effort aimed at structuring the knowledge domain of lifecycle information management through the coupling of physical and digital worlds in the built environment.

nodes.id: A proposed approach to comparing the BIM maturity of countries.pdf
nodes.label: Comparing BIM Maturity of Countries
nodes.desc: This paper proposes three metrics to augment survey data and help establish the overall BIM maturity of countries. The metrics are: NBP availability, NBP content distribution, and NBP relevance. It assesses the knowledge deliverables of the United States, United Kingdom and Australia.

nodes.id: Building Information Modelling Framework- a Research and Delivery Foundation for Industry Stakeholders.pdf
nodes.label: Building Information Modelling Framework
nodes.desc: This paper introduces the BIM Framework, a research and delivery foundation for industry stakeholders. It identifies conceptual parts (fields, stages, steps and lenses), provides examples of their application and identifies visual knowledge models and a specialized ontology to represent domain concepts and their relations.

nodes.label: Measuring BIM performance: Five metrics
nodes.desc: This article identifies five complementary components specifically developed to enable such assessment: (i) BIM capability stages; (ii) BIM maturity levels; (iii) BIM competencies; (iv) Organizational Scales; and (v) Granularity Levels.

nodes.id: Building Information Modeling Analyzing Noteworthy Publications of Eight Countries Using a Knowledge Content Taxonomy.pdf
nodes.label: Building Information Modeling Analyzing Noteworthy Publications...
nodes.desc: This chapter analyzes 57 noteworthy BIM publications from eight countries using a specialized taxonomy. It contributes to organizing BIM knowledge and facilitates targeted access to content by providing a knowledge repository and a research base for identifying and addressing knowledge gaps in the BIM domain.

nodes.id: A Proposed Framework To Investigate Building Information Modelling Through Knowledge Elicitation And Visual Models.pdf
nodes.label: BIM Framework Investigation
nodes.desc: This paper proposes a framework and methodology to investigate BIM through knowledge elicitation and visual models. It identifies BIM concepts, captures BIM interactions, and proposes visual models to elicit expert knowledge.
